title: For Sale:  Chiappa Rhino 40DS .357 Revolver
postcontent:
Excellent condition. Black. 4" Barrel. 

I love this weapon, but with a new baby we are downsizing and I just don't make it to the range much anymore. I have the original case, moon clips, and third-party holster. 

If you haven't shot this "upsidedown" revolver, you should try it. Because of the lower barrel firing out of the 6 o'clock position - .357 buffalo load ammunition feels like a .38S in any other revolver. The aggressive forward-leaning grip puts the entire recoil into your palm, no wrist strain at the end of the day. Even with a heavy double-action trigger pull, the low recoil lets me put all six shots in a tight grouping in only a few seconds. 

Some people call it ugly, but I disagree. The design is impressive. This futuristic revolver can be seen in the recent movies Total Recall and Divergent.

title: For Sale:  1943 WWII Remington 1903a3
location: New Port Richey, Tampa/St. Pete, Florida
postcontent:
For sale is a nice Remington 1903a3 in excellent condition. Serial number is 3510181. The barrel four-grove barrel is marked RA 3-43 with a flaming bomb (Rifle and barrel manufactured in March 1943).

Remington Bolt Marked R with a 9 or 6 within a box. All other parts appear to be Remington manufacture and correct for rifle.

The oil-finished walnut Remington “S” Stock (without Grasping Groves) has a non-serif proof P inside in a half circle (indicating initial test shot) with the number 4 underneath. It is unclear as to what the number 4 below the P indicates. There is a very faint FJA stamped in block letters on the left side above the trigger indicating Lt. Col. Frank J. Atwood oversaw the original Remington Arms Company inspection at Rochester, New York. There are sub assembly stamps by the front of the trigger guard. The stock has two pins below the receiver. (Remington used pins until about July 1943, when they started using bolts. The left rear side of the stock has O.G. stamped within a box indicating the gun was inspected and may have been rebuilt at the end of World War II at the Ogden Arsenal at Hill Air Force Base (HAFB originally called Hill Field) near Ogden, Utah. (A second “P’ would indicate the rifle was rebuilt.) 

The rifle appears to have the original finish which is a parkerized barrel/receiver with most other parts blue/black.

title: For Sale:  NAZI Browning Fabrique Nationale Hi Power 9mm w/original WW II holster
postcontent: This is a late WW II production Browning High Power war trophy. It has been nickeled long ago and shows wear and discoloration with thin surface corrosion in some areas on the slide. See photos. These could likely be removed with fine emery cloth. All Waffenamp marks are present as well as all Nazi acceptance marks of WaA 140 which are correct for this gun made at Fabrique Nationale, Herstal, Belguim. It has pearlite grips in excellent condition. It exhibits the usual characteristics of machining marks in most areas, as the Nazis were far more interested in rapid production during 1944, and not in commercial finishes. The gun's serial number is marked on the frame as 983b, as is the barrel, but the slide has the numbers 47 slightly offset ahead of the 983b. In the mad rush of production at the time, the gun left the factory this way. The holster is original and is in exceptionally sound condition with no rot nor tears nor excessive wear. The holster has the original cleaning rod and provision for a spare magazine. Something was written across the top of the flap, but it has been rubbed off long ago. The holster is made for belt use but also has fittings so idit could be used in a shoulder rig. There is one 13 round magazine which exhibits late war manufacturing characteristics and has an aluminum follower. It is unmarked. An interesting and nice package at an exceptional price. The holster alone is a $250 collector's item. Priority Mail shipping and is $13.00. Insurance, signature, and other postal services are additional cost at the buyer's election. Face to face in Toledo, Ohio, or ship to FFL.

title: For Sale:  Smith & Wesson Model 27-2
postcontent:
This Model 27 has a 3.5" barrel, "standard"/"service"-width trigger (0.265" wide), semi-target hammer (0.375" wide), with a ramped front sight. The shorter barrel and ramped front sight make it ideal for holstered carry, while the narrow trigger is usually better for double-action trigger work. The 3.5" barrel is about as short as the barrel can be while still allowing a full-length ejector rod, which allows the cylinder to be emptied quickly. It has a "pinned" barrel - a cross-pin in the frame that goes through the barrel threads to secure the barrel in place. It also has "recessed" chambers - chamber mouths that are recessed to encompass the cartridge heads when loaded.

It does not have the original wood grip.

I inherited this from my father when he passed away in 2007 and have no additional knowledge about when or where he purchased it.

title: For Sale:  Winchester 12 Pre WWII Nickel Nice Orig 1928 C&R
postcontent: Winchester Model 12 manufactured in 1928 according to the Cody Polishing Room Records. It is an early gun with the last patent date of July, 22 1913 & there is no chamber length stamping. 12 gauge, 2 ¾” chamber, Nickel Steel 30” full choke barrel & is numbers matching, the serial number found on both halves. This is a nice looking honest gun with no extra proofs & all stampings are clear, crisp & 100% legible. There is lots & lots of bluing remaining with no dings, dents, rust or pitting. The blue is mostly limited to the high spots, the bottom from carry & from the travel of the action. Minor handling marks & some freckles are found upon up-close inspection, very nice for a shotgun made before the Great Depression. The stocks are walnut with straight grain & a nice finish. There are no cracks or repairs just minor handling marks & the wood fits proud to the receiver. It has a corn cob pump handle, the butt stock is fluted with a pistol grip, the LOP is just under 14”. Mechanically sound with a smooth crisp action. The bore is bright & shiny, it functions correctly & safely, the take-down feature works properly, the arrows line up & is tight at the halves. 1928 Nickel Steel Winchester Model 12; 87 years old – ready to go needs nothing!

title: Want To Buy:  one Kahr T9, Matte Stainless  / Hogue wood grips
postcontent:
Want to Buy - Has Cash

I am looking for a Kahr T9 in Matte stainless steel with Hogue wood grips, preferably in its original box with all the manuals and magazines.
My father got his car broken into in 2013 and the thief took his T9.  He has been reminiscing since.  He is also getting old and when the time comes, I hopefully will inherit this gun back.
If you have a new or lightly used Kahr T9 (see my definition of lightly used, it has to fall in Grade A, B, C, or D)

Please email me and I will make you a favorable offer for your pistol.  Thanks for reading.

I want your TP and will buy if it is – 
A.	NEW - unused, same condition as factory production, 100% 
B.	UNISSUED / LIKE NEW - unused, but may not have box or factory accessories. May have been sold at retail before, but never used. 99-100% 
C.	USED BUT IN LIKE NEW CONDITION - may have been used slightly, but shows no wear, perfect condition.  Modern guns = 99-100% 
D.	EXCELLENT - may show slight use, no easily apparent mars or defects, minimal bluing wear, mainly slight at edges and muzzle, little to no scratches. Shiny bore. Modern guns = 90-99%, Old guns = 80-99% 

I do not want it, if it is – 
E.	*VERY GOOD PLUS - shows slight wear, only minor defects or dings / scratches. Nice looking bluing but worn at edges and muzzle.  
Modern guns = 85-90%, Old guns = 70-80% 
F.	*VERY GOOD - Everything works, some wear on finish and working surfaces, no corrosion, but maybe some light freckling. Could have minor dents and scratches. Bore may not be shiny but should not be dark.  
Modern guns = 70-85%, Old guns = 60-70% 
G.	*GOOD - Working condition, but finish may be quite worn from sustained use or carry. Wear on working surfaces. Could have some pitting or light corrosion / freckling, and dings or scratches, but they should not interfere with function. May have dark, worn bore. This is the usual condition that surplus guns are graded.  
Modern guns = 50-70%, Old guns = 30-60% 
H.	*FAIR (or ABOUT GOOD) - Still considered working usually, though minor adjustment may be needed Well-worn finish, perhaps no finish left. May have corrosion or pitting that does not render gun unusable. Bore may be shot smooth and be dark. Wood may have cracks but is usually still usable.  
Modern guns = 20-50%, Old guns = 1-30% 
I.	POOR - Adjustment or replacements of parts need, may not be functioning. Worn out or rusty, sold for parts or for repair only, no returns
